 through careful planning and promotion, the city constructed itself as a major tourist attraction. By examining various image-building campaigns and promotional strategies to disseminate a palatable image of New Orleans on a national scale Gotham ultimately establishes New Orleans as one of the originators of the mass tourism industry-which linked leisure to travel, promoted international expositions, and developed the concept of pleasure travel.Gotham shows how New Orleans was able to become one of the most popular tourist attractions in the United States, especially through the transformation of Mardi Gras into a national, even international, event. All the while Gotham is concerned with showing the difference between tourism from above and tourism from below-that is, how New Orleans’ distinctiveness is both maximized, some might say exploited, to serve the global economy of tourism as well as how local groups and individuals use tourism to preserve and anchor longstanding communal traditions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCarnivalzLouisianazNew OrleansxHistory. 0aCity promotionzLouisianazNew OrleansxHistory. 0aCulture and tourismzLouisianazNew OrleansxHistory. 0aExhibitionszLouisianazNew OrleansxHistory. 0aTourismzLouisianazNew OrleansxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh  aGotham.  aKevin.  aOrleans.  aSouthern.  abecame.  acharm.  aexcesses.  aexplains.  aknown.  alocale.  amuch.  aquirky.  aspectacular.  atourist.  atown.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081473185740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814733073423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814733073/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Pr